  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n\n2. Key Federal Criminal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal statute)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. State Statutes:\nMany states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws, though the specific provisions vary by jurisdiction.\n\n4. International Cooperation:\nThe U.S. also participates in international anti-money laundering efforts through organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize financial transactions designed to conceal the source of illegal funds\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Create reporting and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions\n\nThe laws are designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities across various financial sectors.",
